BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 232.40 Tm (sort by salary. The way compareTo works: it compares this object to another and returns a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 217.20 Tm (negative number, zero, or a positive number, meaning 'I come before', 'we are equal', or 'I come) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 202.00 Tm (after'. Use this when there is one obvious, natural way to sort - and when you own the class so) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 186.80 Tm (you can edit it.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 166.60 Tm (The second way is called Comparator, on the right. This is sorting logic written outside the class,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 151.40 Tm (and it is far more flexible. With short lambda expressions you can sort by name, or by salary) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 136.20 Tm (highest-first, or by department and then by salary. You can have as many different sort orders as) Tj ET
