BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 754.00 Tm (method that all vehicles share, but it also has an abstract method, mileage, with no body, that) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 738.80 Tm (each specific vehicle must fill in. So an abstract class gives you some ready-made parts plus some) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 723.60 Tm (blanks to fill. And you cannot create one directly - you cannot say new Vehicle, because it is) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 708.40 Tm (incomplete. You must extend it.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 688.20 Tm (An interface, on the right, is more like a pure list of capabilities. Saveable says 'anything that is) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 673.00 Tm (saveable must have a save method'. The huge advantage is that a class can implement many) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 657.80 Tm (interfaces at once - here, Report is both Printable and Saveable. Remember, a class can only) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 642.60 Tm (extend one parent, but it can implement many interfaces. So interfaces are how Java gives you) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 627.40 Tm (multiple capabilities.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 607.20 Tm (The table sums it up. Quick way to decide: use an abstract class when your classes are closely) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 592.00 Tm (related and share both data and behaviour - like different kinds of vehicles. Use an interface when) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 576.80 Tm (you are giving a capability to possibly unrelated classes - like 'comparable' or 'printable' or) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 561.60 Tm ('runnable'. Those are abilities, not family ties.) Tj ET
