BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 659.00 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 643.00 Tm (This is the practical, everyday way to read and write text files. There is one core idea here, and it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 627.80 Tm (is called wrapping. Let me explain wrapping with an analogy first.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 607.60 Tm (Imagine you are moving books from one room to another. You could carry them one at a time -) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 592.40 Tm (one trip per book - which is painfully slow. Or you could put a box around them, fill the box, and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 577.20 Tm (carry many at once. That box is a buffer. A 'buffered' reader or writer puts a box around the basic) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 562.00 Tm (file tool so it moves data in big efficient chunks instead of one tiny character at a time.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 541.80 Tm (So look at the writing panel. We take a basic FileWriter, wrap it in a BufferedWriter for efficiency,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 526.60 Tm (and then wrap that in a PrintWriter, which adds the friendly println and printf methods you already) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 511.40 Tm (know from printing to the screen. Notice it is all inside try-with-resources, so the file gets closed) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 496.20 Tm (automatically - we will come back to that.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 476.00 Tm (Now the reading panel. We wrap a FileReader in a BufferedReader, and then we read the file one) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 460.80 Tm (line at a time with readLine, inside a while loop. Here is the neat trick - readLine gives back null) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 445.60 Tm (when it reaches the end of the file, and that null naturally stops the loop. Then we split each line by) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 430.40 Tm (commas to pull out the pieces.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 410.20 Tm (So remember the wrapping picture: the BufferedReader wraps the FileReader, which opens the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 395.00 Tm (file. Each layer adds something - one opens, the other adds the efficient buffering and line reading.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 379.80 3.00 285.20 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.700 0.500 0.030 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 368.80 Tm (DELIVERY TIP) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 352.80 Tm (Mention Scanner as the easy alternative they already know - it can read files too, with nextLine and) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 338.40 Tm (nextInt. It is friendlier but slower for big files. BufferedReader is the professional choice for large files.) Tj ET
